<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST: GASTON WINS U.S. WOMEN'S AMATEUR GOLF QUALIFIER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Something about the Old Ranch Country Club in Seal Beach appeals to Andrea 
Gaston of Chatsworth. 
</P>
<P>
 Gaston shot a four-under-par 68 at Old Ranch on Tuesday to take medalist 
honors in a sectional qualifier for the U.S. Women's Amateur, to be held next 
month in Hot Springs, Va. 
</P>
<P>
 Gaston, 36, won a qualifier for the U.S. Women's Open on July 8 at Old Ranch. 
</P>
<P>
 Gaston hit 16 of 18 greens and holed a chip shot for a birdie on another hole. 
</P>
<P>
 "It wasn't a real hard day for my caddie," Gaston said. "She just kept handing 
me the putter every time." 
</P>
<P>
 Gaston led a list of six area players who qualified at Old Ranch -- Linda Chen 
Olsen of Granada Hills, who shot 74 to finish in a two-way tie for second; 
Clarissa Childs of Glendale (77); Jody Duclos of Moorpark (78); Elise Kimm of 
Valley Village (79) and Sylvia Kim of Chatsworth (79). 
</P>
<P>
 Fifteen players at Old Ranch advanced to the U.S. Amateur, to be held Aug. 
8-13 at the Homestead Course. Old Ranch was one of 16 national qualifying 
sites. 
</P>
<P>
 Chen Olsen and Gaston are members of the Porter Valley Country Club. Gaston 
defeated Duclos in the final of the Women's State Amateur championship last 
winter in Monterey. Softball 
</P>
<P>
 The San Fernando Valley-based Stealth went undefeated in a national qualifying 
tournament in Ohio and has qualified to represent California in the American 
Softball Assn. Junior Olympic championships Aug. 10-15 in Greenwood, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
 The team is composed of players aged 12 and under. Maureen LeCocq pitched all 
22 innings in four victories, allowing five hits while striking out 44. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Mermaids All-Star team of Oxnard will begin competition at the under-17 
Pony Girls Softball National Championships at Round Rock, Tex., on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Fifteen players were selected from 388 in the slow-pitch Mermaids softball 
league to compete at the event, which will feature 12 teams from across the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
 Their first game is scheduled for Thursday at 8 a.m. Miscellany 
</P>
<P>
 Chaminade High is looking for a boys' and girls' track coach. 
</P>
<P>
 Ed Croson, the school's athletic director, said a teaching position might be 
available, depending on applicant's qualifications. 
</P>
<P>
 Information: 818-347-8997. 
</P>
