<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOSNIA SERBS TO CLOSE KEY ROUTE INTO SARAJEVO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In a harsh blow to peace prospects, Bosnian Serbs said Tuesday they would 
re-establish their stranglehold on Sarajevo, closing the only route civilians 
can use to enter and leave the city. 
</P>
<P>
 The surprise action, to take effect today, will deprive the Bosnian capital of 
a major food-supply route at a time when the U.N. airlift is indefinitely 
suspended.It will also end a four-month period of near normalcy for Sarajevo, 
the first since Serbs began a bombardment and siege in April, 1992. 
</P>
<P>
 In a letter to the U.N. peacekeeping force, Bosnian Serb leader Radovan 
Karadzic said the road was being closed because the Muslim-led government had 
violated the March agreement that opened the route. 
</P>
<P>
 He accused the government of using the road to smuggle arms and ammunition 
into Sarajevo. He also complained that government troops had been firing into 
Serbian territory and that the government had not honored agreements on 
prisoner exchanges. 
</P>
